00947 {

00949         case OCTEON_CNF75XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
00950         case OCTEON_CN78XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
00951             if (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX))
00952                     return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00016700000010F8ull);
00953             if (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX_PASS1_X))
00954                     return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00016700000010F8ull);
00955         case OCTEON_CN73XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
00956             return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00016700000010F8ull);
00957             break;
00958         case OCTEON_CN68XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
00959             return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00016700000010F0ull);
00960             break;
00961     }
00962     cvmx_warn("CVMX_SSO_RESET not supported on this chip\n");
00963     return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00016700000010F8ull);
00964 }
00965 #else
00966 #define CVMX_SSO_RESET CVMX_SSO_RESET_FUNC()
00967 static inline uint64_t CVMX_SSO_RESET_FUNC(void)
00968 {
00969     switch(cvmx_get_octeon_family()) {
00970         case OCTEON_CNF75XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
00971         case OCTEON_CN78XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
00972             if (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX))
00973                 return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00016700000010F8ull);
00974             if (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX_PASS1_X))
00975                 return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00016700000010F8ull);
00976         case OCTEON_CN73XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
00977             return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00016700000010F8ull);
00978         case OCTEON_CN68XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
00979             return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x00016700000010F0ull);

01401 /**
01402  * cvmx_sso_active_cycles
01403  *
01404  * SSO_ACTIVE_CYCLES = SSO cycles SSO active
01405  *
01406  * This register counts every sclk cycle that the SSO clocks are active.
01407  * **NOTE: Added in pass 2.0
01408  */
01409 union cvmx_sso_active_cycles {
01410     uint64_t u64;
01411     struct cvmx_sso_active_cycles_s {
01412 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01413     uint64_t act_cyc                      : 64; /**< Counts number of active cycles. */
01414 #else
01415     uint64_t act_cyc                      : 64;
01416 #endif
01417     } s;
01418     struct cvmx_sso_active_cycles_s       cn68xx;
01419 };
01420 typedef union cvmx_sso_active_cycles cvmx_sso_active_cycles_t;
01421 
01422 /**
01423  * cvmx_sso_active_cycles#
01424  *
01425  * This register counts every coprocessor clock (SCLK) cycle that the SSO clocks are active.
01426  *
01427  */
01428 union cvmx_sso_active_cyclesx {
01429     uint64_t u64;
01430     struct cvmx_sso_active_cyclesx_s {
01431 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01432     uint64_t act_cyc                      : 64; /**< Counts the number of active cycles in each conditional clock domain. */
01433 #else
01434     uint64_t act_cyc                      : 64;
01435 #endif
01436     } s;
01437     struct cvmx_sso_active_cyclesx_s      cn73xx;
01438     struct cvmx_sso_active_cyclesx_s      cn78xx;
01439     struct cvmx_sso_active_cyclesx_s      cn78xxp1;
01440     struct cvmx_sso_active_cyclesx_s      cnf75xx;
01441 };
01442 typedef union cvmx_sso_active_cyclesx cvmx_sso_active_cyclesx_t;
01443 
01444 /**
01445  * cvmx_sso_aw_add
01446  */
01447 union cvmx_sso_aw_add {
01448     uint64_t u64;
01449     struct cvmx_sso_aw_add_s {
01450 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01451     uint64_t reserved_30_63               : 34;
01452     uint64_t rsvd_free                    : 14; /**< Written value is added to SSO_AW_WE[RSVD_FREE] to prevent races between software and
01453                                                          hardware changes. This is a two's complement value so subtraction may also be performed. */
01454     uint64_t reserved_0_15                : 16;
01455 #else
01456     uint64_t reserved_0_15                : 16;
01457     uint64_t rsvd_free                    : 14;
01458     uint64_t reserved_30_63               : 34;
01459 #endif
01460     } s;
01461     struct cvmx_sso_aw_add_s              cn73xx;
01462     struct cvmx_sso_aw_add_s              cn78xx;
01463     struct cvmx_sso_aw_add_s              cn78xxp1;
01464     struct cvmx_sso_aw_add_s              cnf75xx;

01468 /**
01469  * cvmx_sso_aw_cfg
01470  *
01471  * This register controls the operation of the add-work block (AW).
01472  *
01473  */
01474 union cvmx_sso_aw_cfg {
01475     uint64_t u64;
01476     struct cvmx_sso_aw_cfg_s {
01477 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01478     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
01479     uint64_t ldt_short                    : 1;  /**< Use LDT to bypass L2 allocations when reading short form work. */
01480     uint64_t lol                          : 1;  /**< Reserved. */
01481     uint64_t xaq_alloc_dis                : 1;  /**< Disable FPA alloc requests to fill the SSO page cache. Also all existing cached free
01482                                                          buffers will be returned to FPA and will not be cached. */
01483     uint64_t ocla_bp                      : 1;  /**< OCLA backpressure enable. When OCLA FIFOs are near full, allow OCLA to backpressure AW pipeline. */
01484     uint64_t xaq_byp_dis                  : 1;  /**< Disable bypass path in add-work engine. For diagnostic use only. */
01485     uint64_t stt                          : 1;  /**< Use STT to bypass L2 allocation for XAQ store operations. */
01486     uint64_t ldt                          : 1;  /**< Use LDT to bypass L2 allocation for XAQ load operations. */
01487     uint64_t ldwb                         : 1;  /**< When reading XAQ cache lines, use LDWB transactions to invalidate the cache line. */
01488     uint64_t rwen                         : 1;  /**< Enable XAQ operations. This bit should be set after SSO_XAQ()_HEAD_PTR and
01489                                                          SSO_XAQ()_TAIL_PTR have been programmed. If cleared, all cached buffers will be
01490                                                          returned from the FPA as soon as possible, and TAQ arbitration is simplified. */
01491 #else
01492     uint64_t rwen                         : 1;
01493     uint64_t ldwb                         : 1;
01494     uint64_t ldt                          : 1;
01495     uint64_t stt                          : 1;
01496     uint64_t xaq_byp_dis                  : 1;
01497     uint64_t ocla_bp                      : 1;
01498     uint64_t xaq_alloc_dis                : 1;
01499     uint64_t lol                          : 1;
01500     uint64_t ldt_short                    : 1;
01501     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
01502 #endif
01503     } s;
01504     struct cvmx_sso_aw_cfg_s              cn73xx;
01505     struct cvmx_sso_aw_cfg_s              cn78xx;

01844 /**
01845  * cvmx_sso_cfg
01846  *
01847  * SSO_CFG = SSO Config
01848  *
01849  * This register is an assortment of various SSO configuration bits.
01850  */
01851 union cvmx_sso_cfg {
01852     uint64_t u64;
01853     struct cvmx_sso_cfg_s {
01854 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01855     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
01856     uint64_t qck_gw_rsp_adj               : 3;  /**< Fast GET_WORK response fine adjustment
01857                                                          Allowed values are 0, 1, and 2 (0 is quickest) */
01858     uint64_t qck_gw_rsp_dis               : 1;  /**< Disable faster response to GET_WORK */
01859     uint64_t qck_sw_dis                   : 1;  /**< Disable faster switch to UNSCHEDULED on GET_WORK */
01860     uint64_t rwq_alloc_dis                : 1;  /**< Disable FPA Alloc Requests when SSO_FPAGE_CNT < 16 */
01861     uint64_t soc_ccam_dis                 : 1;  /**< Disable power saving SOC conditional CAM
01862                                                          (**NOTE: Added in pass 2.0) */
01863     uint64_t sso_cclk_dis                 : 1;  /**< Disable power saving SSO conditional clocking
01864                                                          (**NOTE: Added in pass 2.0) */
01865     uint64_t rwo_flush                    : 1;  /**< Flush RWO engine
01866                                                          Allows outbound NCB entries to go immediately rather
01867                                                          than waiting for a complete fill packet. This register
01868                                                          is one-shot and clears itself each time it is set. */
01869     uint64_t wfe_thr                      : 1;  /**< Use 1 Work-fetch engine (instead of 4) */
01870     uint64_t rwio_byp_dis                 : 1;  /**< Disable Bypass path in RWI/RWO Engines */
01871     uint64_t rwq_byp_dis                  : 1;  /**< Disable Bypass path in RWQ Engine */
01872     uint64_t stt                          : 1;  /**< STT Setting for RW Stores */
01873     uint64_t ldt                          : 1;  /**< LDT Setting for RW Loads */
01874     uint64_t dwb                          : 1;  /**< DWB Setting for Return Page Requests
01875                                                          1 = 2 128B cache pages to issue DWB for
01876                                                          0 = 0 128B cache pages ro issue DWB for */
01877     uint64_t rwen                         : 1;  /**< Enable RWI/RWO operations
01878                                                          This bit should be set after SSO_RWQ_HEAD_PTRX and
01879                                                          SSO_RWQ_TAIL_PTRX have been programmed. */
01880 #else
01881     uint64_t rwen                         : 1;
01882     uint64_t dwb                          : 1;
01883     uint64_t ldt                          : 1;
01884     uint64_t stt                          : 1;
01885     uint64_t rwq_byp_dis                  : 1;
01886     uint64_t rwio_byp_dis                 : 1;
01887     uint64_t wfe_thr                      : 1;
01888     uint64_t rwo_flush                    : 1;
01889     uint64_t sso_cclk_dis                 : 1;
01890     uint64_t soc_ccam_dis                 : 1;
01891     uint64_t rwq_alloc_dis                : 1;
01892     uint64_t qck_sw_dis                   : 1;
01893     uint64_t qck_gw_rsp_dis               : 1;
01894     uint64_t qck_gw_rsp_adj               : 3;
01895     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
01896 #endif
01897     } s;
01898     struct cvmx_sso_cfg_s                 cn68xx;
01899     struct cvmx_sso_cfg_cn68xxp1 {
01900 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01901     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
01902     uint64_t rwo_flush                    : 1;  /**< Flush RWO engine
01903                                                          Allows outbound NCB entries to go immediately rather
01904                                                          than waiting for a complete fill packet. This register
01905                                                          is one-shot and clears itself each time it is set. */
01906     uint64_t wfe_thr                      : 1;  /**< Use 1 Work-fetch engine (instead of 4) */
01907     uint64_t rwio_byp_dis                 : 1;  /**< Disable Bypass path in RWI/RWO Engines */
01908     uint64_t rwq_byp_dis                  : 1;  /**< Disable Bypass path in RWQ Engine */
01909     uint64_t stt                          : 1;  /**< STT Setting for RW Stores */
01910     uint64_t ldt                          : 1;  /**< LDT Setting for RW Loads */
01911     uint64_t dwb                          : 1;  /**< DWB Setting for Return Page Requests
01912                                                          1 = 2 128B cache pages to issue DWB for
01913                                                          0 = 0 128B cache pages ro issue DWB for */

01915                                                          This bit should be set after SSO_RWQ_HEAD_PTRX and
01916                                                          SSO_RWQ_TAIL_PTRX have been programmed. */

01919     uint64_t dwb                          : 1;
01920     uint64_t ldt                          : 1;
01921     uint64_t stt                          : 1;

01927 #endif

02102 /**
02103  * cvmx_sso_err
02104  *
02105  * SSO_ERR = SSO Error Register
02106  *
02107  * Contains ECC and other misc error bits.
02108  *
02109  * <45> The free page error bit will assert when SSO_FPAGE_CNT <= 16 and
02110  *      SSO_CFG[RWEN] is 1.  Software will want to disable the interrupt
02111  *      associated with this error when recovering SSO pointers from the
02112  *      FPA and SSO.
02113  *
02114  * This register also contains the illegal operation error bits:
02115  *
02116  * <42> Received ADDWQ with tag specified as EMPTY
02117  * <41> Received illegal opcode
02118  * <40> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/UPD_WQP/GET_WORK/ALLOC_WE
02119  *      from WS with CLR_NSCHED pending
02120  * <39> Received CLR_NSCHED
02121  *      from WS with SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/CLR_NSCHED pending
02122  * <38> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/UPD_WQP/GET_WORK/ALLOC_WE
02123  *      from WS with ALLOC_WE pending
02124  * <37> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/UPD_WQP/GET_WORK/ALLOC_WE/CLR_NSCHED
02125  *      from WS with GET_WORK pending
02126  * <36> Received SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH
02127  *      with tag specified as UNSCHEDULED
02128  * <35> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH
02129  *      with tag specified as EMPTY
02130  * <34> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH/GET_WORK
02131  *      from WS with pending tag switch to ORDERED or ATOMIC
02132  * <33> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/UPD_WQP
02133  *      from WS in UNSCHEDULED state
02134  * <32> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/UPD_WQP
02135  *      from WS in EMPTY state
02136  */
02137 union cvmx_sso_err {
02138     uint64_t u64;
02139     struct cvmx_sso_err_s {
02140 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02141     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
02142     uint64_t bfp                          : 1;  /**< Bad Fill Packet error
02143                                                          Last byte of the fill packet did not match 8'h1a */
02144     uint64_t awe                          : 1;  /**< Out-of-memory error (ADDWQ Request is dropped) */
02145     uint64_t fpe                          : 1;  /**< Free page error */
02146     uint64_t reserved_43_44               : 2;
02147     uint64_t iop                          : 11; /**< Illegal operation errors */
02148     uint64_t reserved_12_31               : 20;
02149     uint64_t pnd_dbe0                     : 1;  /**< Double bit error for even PND RAM */
02150     uint64_t pnd_sbe0                     : 1;  /**< Single bit error for even PND RAM */
02151     uint64_t pnd_dbe1                     : 1;  /**< Double bit error for odd PND RAM */
02152     uint64_t pnd_sbe1                     : 1;  /**< Single bit error for odd PND RAM */
02153     uint64_t oth_dbe0                     : 1;  /**< Double bit error for even OTH RAM */
02154     uint64_t oth_sbe0                     : 1;  /**< Single bit error for even OTH RAM */
02155     uint64_t oth_dbe1                     : 1;  /**< Double bit error for odd OTH RAM */
02156     uint64_t oth_sbe1                     : 1;  /**< Single bit error for odd OTH RAM */
02157     uint64_t idx_dbe                      : 1;  /**< Double bit error for IDX RAM */
02158     uint64_t idx_sbe                      : 1;  /**< Single bit error for IDX RAM */
02159     uint64_t fidx_dbe                     : 1;  /**< Double bit error for FIDX RAM */
02160     uint64_t fidx_sbe                     : 1;  /**< Single bit error for FIDX RAM */
02161 #else
02162     uint64_t fidx_sbe                     : 1;
02163     uint64_t fidx_dbe                     : 1;
02164     uint64_t idx_sbe                      : 1;
02165     uint64_t idx_dbe                      : 1;
02166     uint64_t oth_sbe1                     : 1;
02167     uint64_t oth_dbe1                     : 1;
02168     uint64_t oth_sbe0                     : 1;
02169     uint64_t oth_dbe0                     : 1;
02170     uint64_t pnd_sbe1                     : 1;
02171     uint64_t pnd_dbe1                     : 1;
02172     uint64_t pnd_sbe0                     : 1;
02173     uint64_t pnd_dbe0                     : 1;
02174     uint64_t reserved_12_31               : 20;
02175     uint64_t iop                          : 11;
02176     uint64_t reserved_43_44               : 2;
02177     uint64_t fpe                          : 1;
02178     uint64_t awe                          : 1;
02179     uint64_t bfp                          : 1;
02180     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
02181 #endif
02182     } s;
02183     struct cvmx_sso_err_s                 cn68xx;
02184     struct cvmx_sso_err_s                 cn68xxp1;
02185 };

02648 /**
02649  * cvmx_sso_grp#_int
02650  *
02651  * Contains the per-group interrupts and are used to clear these interrupts. For more information
02652  * on this register, refer to Interrupts.
02653  */
02654 union cvmx_sso_grpx_int {
02655     uint64_t u64;
02656     struct cvmx_sso_grpx_int_s {
02657 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02658     uint64_t exe_dis                      : 1;  /**< Executable interrupt temporary disable. Corresponding [EXE_INT] bit cannot be set due to
02659                                                          IAQ_CNT/IAQ_THR check when this bit is set. EXE_DIS is cleared by hardware whenever:
02660                                                          * SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[IAQ_CNT] is zero, or
02661                                                          * The hardware decrements the time counter for this group to zero, i.e.
02662                                                          SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[TC_CNT] is equal to 1 when periodic counter SSO_WQ_INT_PC[PC] is
02663                                                          equal to 0. */
02664     uint64_t reserved_2_62                : 61;
02665     uint64_t exe_int                      : 1;  /**< Work-executable interrupt. Generally used to indicate work is waiting for software. Throws
02666                                                          SSO_INTSN_E::SSO_GRP()_EXE. Set by hardware whenever:
02667                                                          * SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[IAQ_CNT] >= SSO_GRP()_INT_THR [IAQ_THR] and [IAQ_THR] != 0
02668                                                          and EXE_DIS is clear.
02669                                                          * SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[DS_CNT] >= SSO_GRP()_INT_THR[DS_THR] and [DS_THR] != 0.
02670                                                          * SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[CQ_CNT] >= SSO_GRP()_INT_THR[CQ_THR] and [CQ_THR] != 0.
02671                                                          * SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[TC_CNT] is equal to 1 when periodic counter SSO_WQ_INT_PC[PC] is
02672                                                          equal to 0 and SSO_GRP()_INT_THR[TC_EN] is set and at least one of the following is
02673                                                          true:
02674                                                          _ SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[IAQ_CNT] > 0
02675                                                          _ SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[DS_CNT] > 0
02676                                                          _ SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[CQ_CNT] > 0 */
02677     uint64_t aq_int                       : 1;  /**< External group queue threshold interrupt. Set if SSO_GRP()_AQ_CNT changes, and the
02678                                                          resulting value is equal to SSO_GRP()_AQ_THR. Throws
02679                                                          SSO_INTSN_E::SSO_GRP()_AQ. */
02680 #else
02681     uint64_t aq_int                       : 1;
02682     uint64_t exe_int                      : 1;
02683     uint64_t reserved_2_62                : 61;
02684     uint64_t exe_dis                      : 1;
02685 #endif
02686     } s;

02688     struct cvmx_sso_grpx_int_s            cn78xx;
02689     struct cvmx_sso_grpx_int_s            cn78xxp1;

02706                                                          SSO_GRP()_INT_THR[TC_THR] whenever:
02707                                                          * Corresponding SSO_GRP()_INT_CNT[IAQ_CNT, DS_CNT and CQ_CNT] are all equal to 0x0.
02708                                                          * Corresponding SSO_GRP()_INT[EXE_INT] is written with a one to clear by software.
02709                                                          * Corresponding SSO_GRP()_INT[EXE_DIS] is written with a one to set by software.
02710                                                          * Corresponding SSO_GRP()_INT_THR is written by software.
02711                                                          * TC_CNT is equal to 1 and periodic counter SSO_WQ_INT_PC[PC] is equal to 0x0.
02712                                                          Otherwise, hardware decrements this field whenever the periodic counter SSO_WQ_INT_PC[PC]

02718     uint64_t reserved_13_15               : 3;
02719     uint64_t iaq_cnt                      : 13; /**< Work-queue entries for this in-unit admission queue. */
02720 #else

02723     uint64_t ds_cnt                       : 13;
02724     uint64_t reserved_29_31               : 3;
02725     uint64_t cq_cnt                       : 13;
02726     uint64_t reserved_45_47               : 3;

03877 /**
03878  * cvmx_sso_pp#_grp_msk

03880  * CSR reserved addresses: (24): 0x5040..0x50f8
03881  * CSR align addresses: ===========================================================================================================
03882  * SSO_PPX_GRP_MSK = SSO PP Group Mask Register
03883  *                   (one bit per group per PP)
03884  *
03885  * Selects which group(s) a PP belongs to.  A '1' in any bit position sets the
03886  * PP's membership in the corresponding group.  A value of 0x0 will prevent the
03887  * PP from receiving new work.
03888  *
03889  * Note that these do not contain QOS level priorities for each PP.  This is a
03890  * change from previous POW designs.
03891  */

03906 /**
03907  * cvmx_sso_pp#_qos_pri
03908  *
03909  * CSR reserved addresses: (56): 0x2040..0x21f8
03910  * CSR align addresses: ===========================================================================================================
03911  * SSO_PP(0..31)_QOS_PRI = SSO PP QOS Priority Register
03912  *                                (one field per IQ per PP)
03913  *
03914  * Contains the QOS level priorities for each PP.
03915  *      0x0       is the highest priority
03916  *      0x7       is the lowest priority
03917  *      0xf       prevents the PP from receiving work from that QOS level
03918  *      0x8-0xe   Reserved
03919  *
03920  * For a given PP, priorities should begin at 0x0, and remain contiguous
03921  * throughout the range.  Failure to do so may result in severe
03922  * performance degradation.
03923  *
03924  *
03925  * Priorities for IQs 0..7
03926  */

03933     uint64_t reserved_52_55               : 4;

03935     uint64_t reserved_44_47               : 4;

03941     uint64_t reserved_20_23               : 4;

03982                                                          group for groups <63:0>.
03983                                                          A value of 0x0 in GRPMSK for a given core prevents the core from receiving new
03984                                                          work. Cores that will never receive work should use GRPMSK=0x0; while this setting
03985                                                          is not special in SSO, for backward and forward compatibility this may enable reallocation
03986                                                          of internal resources to the remaining (nonzero-mask) cores. */
03987 #else

03989 #endif
03990     } s;

03997 
03998 /**
03999  * cvmx_sso_pp_strict
04000  *
04001  * SSO_PP_STRICT = SSO Strict Priority
04002  *
04003  * This register controls getting work from the input queues.  If the bit
04004  * corresponding to a PP is set, that PP will not take work off the input
04005  * queues until it is known that there is no higher-priority work available.
04006  *
04007  * Setting SSO_PP_STRICT may incur a performance penalty if highest-priority
04008  * work is not found early.
04009  *
04010  * It is possible to starve a PP of work with SSO_PP_STRICT.  If the
04011  * SSO_PPX_GRP_MSK for a PP masks-out much of the work added to the input
04012  * queues that are higher-priority for that PP, and if there is a constant
04013  * stream of work through one or more of those higher-priority input queues,
04014  * then that PP may not accept work from lower-priority input queues.  This can
04015  * be alleviated by ensuring that most or all the work added to the
04016  * higher-priority input queues for a PP with SSO_PP_STRICT set are in a group
04017  * acceptable to that PP.
04018  *
04019  * It is also possible to neglect work in an input queue if SSO_PP_STRICT is
04020  * used.  If an input queue is a lower-priority queue for all PPs, and if all
04021  * the PPs have their corresponding bit in SSO_PP_STRICT set, then work may
04022  * never be taken (or be seldom taken) from that queue.  This can be alleviated
04023  * by ensuring that work in all input queues can be serviced by one or more PPs
04024  * that do not have SSO_PP_STRICT set, or that the input queue is the
04025  * highest-priority input queue for one or more PPs that do have SSO_PP_STRICT
04026  * set.
04027  */
04028 union cvmx_sso_pp_strict {
04029     uint64_t u64;
04030     struct cvmx_sso_pp_strict_s {
04031 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04032     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
04033     uint64_t pp_strict                    : 32; /**< Corresponding PP operates in strict mode. */
04034 #else
04035     uint64_t pp_strict                    : 32;
04036     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
04037 #endif
04038     } s;
04039     struct cvmx_sso_pp_strict_s           cn68xx;
04040     struct cvmx_sso_pp_strict_s           cn68xxp1;
04041 };
04042 typedef union cvmx_sso_pp_strict cvmx_sso_pp_strict_t;
04043 
04044 /**
04045  * cvmx_sso_qos#_rnd
04046  *
04047  * CSR align addresses: ===========================================================================================================
04048  * SSO_QOS(0..7)_RND = SSO QOS Issue Round Register
04049  *                (one per IQ)
04050  *
04051  * The number of arbitration rounds each QOS level participates in.
04052  */
04053 union cvmx_sso_qosx_rnd {
04054     uint64_t u64;

04056 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04057     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
04058     uint64_t rnds_qos                     : 8;  /**< Number of rounds to participate in for IQ(X). */
04059 #else
04060     uint64_t rnds_qos                     : 8;
04061     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
04062 #endif
04063     } s;
04064     struct cvmx_sso_qosx_rnd_s            cn68xx;
04065     struct cvmx_sso_qosx_rnd_s            cn68xxp1;
04066 };
04067 typedef union cvmx_sso_qosx_rnd cvmx_sso_qosx_rnd_t;
04068 
04069 /**
04070  * cvmx_sso_qos_thr#
04071  *
04072  * CSR reserved addresses: (24): 0xa040..0xa0f8
04073  * CSR align addresses: ===========================================================================================================
04074  * SSO_QOS_THRX = SSO QOS Threshold Register
04075  *                (one per QOS level)
04076  *
04077  * Contains the thresholds for allocating SSO internal storage buffers.  If the
04078  * number of remaining free buffers drops below the minimum threshold (MIN_THR)
04079  * or the number of allocated buffers for this QOS level rises above the
04080  * maximum threshold (MAX_THR), future incoming work queue entries will be
04081  * buffered externally rather than internally.  This register also contains the
04082  * number of internal buffers currently allocated to this QOS level (BUF_CNT).
04083  */
04084 union cvmx_sso_qos_thrx {
04085     uint64_t u64;
04086     struct cvmx_sso_qos_thrx_s {
04087 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04088     uint64_t reserved_40_63               : 24;
04089     uint64_t buf_cnt                      : 12; /**< # of internal buffers allocated to QOS level X */
04090     uint64_t reserved_26_27               : 2;
04091     uint64_t max_thr                      : 12; /**< Max threshold for QOS level X
04092                                                          For performance reasons, MAX_THR can have a slop of 6
04093                                                          WQE for QOS level X. */
04094     uint64_t reserved_12_13               : 2;
04095     uint64_t min_thr                      : 12; /**< Min threshold for QOS level X
04096                                                          For performance reasons, MIN_THR can have a slop of 6
04097                                                          WQEs for QOS level X. */
04098 #else
04099     uint64_t min_thr                      : 12;
04100     uint64_t reserved_12_13               : 2;
04101     uint64_t max_thr                      : 12;
04102     uint64_t reserved_26_27               : 2;
04103     uint64_t buf_cnt                      : 12;
04104     uint64_t reserved_40_63               : 24;
04105 #endif
04106     } s;
04107     struct cvmx_sso_qos_thrx_s            cn68xx;
04108     struct cvmx_sso_qos_thrx_s            cn68xxp1;
04109 };
04110 typedef union cvmx_sso_qos_thrx cvmx_sso_qos_thrx_t;

04112 /**
04113  * cvmx_sso_qos_we
04114  *
04115  * SSO_QOS_WE = SSO WE Buffers
04116  *
04117  * This register contains a read-only count of the current number of free
04118  * buffers (FREE_CNT) and the total number of tag chain heads on the de-schedule list
04119  * (DES_CNT) (which is not the same as the total number of entries on all of the descheduled
04120  * tag chains.)
04121  */
04122 union cvmx_sso_qos_we {

04128     uint64_t reserved_12_13               : 2;
04129     uint64_t free_cnt                     : 12; /**< Number of total free buffers */
04130 #else
04131     uint64_t free_cnt                     : 12;
04132     uint64_t reserved_12_13               : 2;
04133     uint64_t des_cnt                      : 12;
04134     uint64_t reserved_26_63               : 38;
04135 #endif
04136     } s;
04137     struct cvmx_sso_qos_we_s              cn68xx;
04138     struct cvmx_sso_qos_we_s              cn68xxp1;

04142 /**
04143  * cvmx_sso_reset
04144  *
04145  * Writing a 1 to SSO_RESET[RESET] resets the SSO. After receiving a store to this CSR, the SSO
04146  * must not be sent any other operations for 2500 coprocessor (SCLK) cycles. Note that the
04147  * contents of this register are reset along with the rest of the SSO.
04148  */
04149 union cvmx_sso_reset {
04150     uint64_t u64;
04151     struct cvmx_sso_reset_s {
04152 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04153     uint64_t busy                         : 1;  /**< Initialization in progress. After reset asserts, SSO will set this bit until internal
04154                                                          structures are initialized. This bit must read as zero before any configuration may be
04155                                                          done. */
04156     uint64_t reserved_1_62                : 62;
04157     uint64_t reset                        : 1;  /**< Reset the SSO. */
04158 #else
04159     uint64_t reset                        : 1;
04160     uint64_t reserved_1_62                : 62;
04161     uint64_t busy                         : 1;
04162 #endif
04163     } s;
04164     struct cvmx_sso_reset_cn68xx {
04165 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04166     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
04167     uint64_t reset                        : 1;  /**< Reset the SSO */
04168 #else
04169     uint64_t reset                        : 1;
04170     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
04171 #endif
04172     } cn68xx;
04173     struct cvmx_sso_reset_s               cn73xx;
04174     struct cvmx_sso_reset_s               cn78xx;
04175     struct cvmx_sso_reset_s               cn78xxp1;
04176     struct cvmx_sso_reset_s               cnf75xx;
04177 };

04180 /**
04181  * cvmx_sso_rwq_head_ptr#
04182  *
04183  * CSR reserved addresses: (24): 0xb040..0xb0f8
04184  * CSR align addresses: ===========================================================================================================
04185  * SSO_RWQ_HEAD_PTRX = SSO Remote Queue Head Register
04186  *                (one per QOS level)
04187  * Contains the ptr to the first entry of the remote linked list(s) for a particular
04188  * QoS level. SW should initialize the remote linked list(s) by programming
04189  * SSO_RWQ_HEAD_PTRX and SSO_RWQ_TAIL_PTRX to identical values.
04190  */
04191 union cvmx_sso_rwq_head_ptrx {

04194 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04195     uint64_t reserved_38_63               : 26;
04196     uint64_t ptr                          : 31; /**< Head Pointer */
04197     uint64_t reserved_5_6                 : 2;
04198     uint64_t rctr                         : 5;  /**< Index of next WQE entry in fill packet to be
04199                                                          processed (inbound queues) */
04200 #else
04201     uint64_t rctr                         : 5;
04202     uint64_t reserved_5_6                 : 2;
04203     uint64_t ptr                          : 31;
04204     uint64_t reserved_38_63               : 26;
04205 #endif
04206     } s;
04207     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_head_ptrx_s       cn68xx;
04208     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_head_ptrx_s       cn68xxp1;
04209 };
04210 typedef union cvmx_sso_rwq_head_ptrx cvmx_sso_rwq_head_ptrx_t;
04211 
04212 /**
04213  * cvmx_sso_rwq_pop_fptr
04214  *
04215  * SSO_RWQ_POP_FPTR = SSO Pop Free Pointer
04216  *
04217  * This register is used by SW to remove pointers for buffer-reallocation and diagnostics, and
04218  * should only be used when SSO is idle.
04219  *
04220  * To remove ALL pointers, software must insure that there are modulus 16
04221  * pointers in the FPA.  To do this, SSO_CFG.RWQ_BYP_DIS must be set, the FPA
04222  * pointer count read, and enough fake buffers pushed via SSO_RWQ_PSH_FPTR to
04223  * bring the FPA pointer count up to mod 16.
04224  */
04225 union cvmx_sso_rwq_pop_fptr {
04226     uint64_t u64;
04227     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_pop_fptr_s {
04228 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04229     uint64_t val                          : 1;  /**< Free Pointer Valid */
04230     uint64_t reserved_38_62               : 25;
04231     uint64_t fptr                         : 31; /**< Free Pointer */
04232     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
04233 #else
04234     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
04235     uint64_t fptr                         : 31;
04236     uint64_t reserved_38_62               : 25;
04237     uint64_t val                          : 1;
04238 #endif
04239     } s;
04240     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_pop_fptr_s        cn68xx;
04241     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_pop_fptr_s        cn68xxp1;
04242 };
04243 typedef union cvmx_sso_rwq_pop_fptr cvmx_sso_rwq_pop_fptr_t;
04244 
04245 /**
04246  * cvmx_sso_rwq_psh_fptr
04247  *
04248  * CSR reserved addresses: (56): 0xc240..0xc3f8
04249  * SSO_RWQ_PSH_FPTR = SSO Free Pointer FIFO
04250  *
04251  * This register is used by SW to initialize the SSO with a pool of free
04252  * pointers by writing the FPTR field whenever FULL = 0. Free pointers are
04253  * fetched/released from/to the pool when accessing WQE entries stored remotely
04254  * (in remote linked lists).  Free pointers should be 128 byte aligned, each of
04255  * 256 bytes. This register should only be used when SSO is idle.
04256  *
04257  * Software needs to set aside buffering for
04258  *      8 + 48 + ROUNDUP(N/26)
04259  *
04260  * where as many as N DRAM work queue entries may be used.  The first 8 buffers
04261  * are used to setup the SSO_RWQ_HEAD_PTR and SSO_RWQ_TAIL_PTRs, and the
04262  * remainder are pushed via this register.
04263  *
04264  * IMPLEMENTATION NOTES--NOT FOR SPEC:
04265  *      48 avoids false out of buffer error due to (16) FPA and in-sso FPA buffering (32)
04266  *      26 is number of WAE's per 256B buffer
04267  */
04268 union cvmx_sso_rwq_psh_fptr {
04269     uint64_t u64;
04270     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_psh_fptr_s {
04271 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04272     uint64_t full                         : 1;  /**< FIFO Full.  When set, the FPA is busy writing entries
04273                                                          and software must wait before adding new entries. */
04274     uint64_t reserved_38_62               : 25;
04275     uint64_t fptr                         : 31; /**< Free Pointer */
04276     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
04277 #else
04278     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
04279     uint64_t fptr                         : 31;
04280     uint64_t reserved_38_62               : 25;
04281     uint64_t full                         : 1;
04282 #endif
04283     } s;
04284     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_psh_fptr_s        cn68xx;
04285     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_psh_fptr_s        cn68xxp1;
04286 };
04287 typedef union cvmx_sso_rwq_psh_fptr cvmx_sso_rwq_psh_fptr_t;
04288 
04289 /**
04290  * cvmx_sso_rwq_tail_ptr#
04291  *
04292  * CSR reserved addresses: (56): 0xc040..0xc1f8
04293  * SSO_RWQ_TAIL_PTRX = SSO Remote Queue Tail Register
04294  *                (one per QOS level)
04295  * Contains the ptr to the last entry of the remote linked list(s) for a particular
04296  * QoS level. SW must initialize the remote linked list(s) by programming
04297  * SSO_RWQ_HEAD_PTRX and SSO_RWQ_TAIL_PTRX to identical values.
04298  */
04299 union cvmx_sso_rwq_tail_ptrx {
04300     uint64_t u64;
04301     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_tail_ptrx_s {
04302 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04303     uint64_t reserved_38_63               : 26;
04304     uint64_t ptr                          : 31; /**< Tail Pointer */
04305     uint64_t reserved_5_6                 : 2;
04306     uint64_t rctr                         : 5;  /**< Number of entries waiting to be sent out to external
04307                                                          RAM (outbound queues) */
04308 #else
04309     uint64_t rctr                         : 5;
04310     uint64_t reserved_5_6                 : 2;
04311     uint64_t ptr                          : 31;
04312     uint64_t reserved_38_63               : 26;
04313 #endif
04314     } s;
04315     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_tail_ptrx_s       cn68xx;
04316     struct cvmx_sso_rwq_tail_ptrx_s       cn68xxp1;
04317 };

04924 /**
04925  * cvmx_sso_wq_int
04926  *
04927  * Note, the old POW offsets ran from 0x0 to 0x3f8, leaving the next available slot at 0x400.
04928  * To ensure no overlap, start on 4k boundary: 0x1000.
04929  * SSO_WQ_INT = SSO Work Queue Interrupt Register
04930  *
04931  * Contains the bits (one per group) that set work queue interrupts and are
04932  * used to clear these interrupts.  For more information regarding this
04933  * register, see the interrupt section of the SSO spec.
04934  */
04935 union cvmx_sso_wq_int {
04936     uint64_t u64;
04937     struct cvmx_sso_wq_int_s {
04938 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04939     uint64_t wq_int                       : 64; /**< Work queue interrupt bits
04940                                                          Corresponding WQ_INT bit is set by HW whenever:
04941                                                            - SSO_WQ_INT_CNTX[IQ_CNT] >=
04942                                                              SSO_WQ_INT_THRX[IQ_THR] and the threshold
04943                                                              interrupt is not disabled.
04944                                                              SSO_WQ_IQ_DISX[IQ_DIS<X>]==1 disables the interrupt
04945                                                              SSO_WQ_INT_THRX[IQ_THR]==0 disables the int.
04946                                                            - SSO_WQ_INT_CNTX[DS_CNT] >=
04947                                                              SSO_WQ_INT_THRX[DS_THR] and the threshold
04948                                                              interrupt is not disabled
04949                                                              SSO_WQ_INT_THRX[DS_THR]==0 disables the int.
04950                                                            - SSO_WQ_INT_CNTX[TC_CNT]==1 when periodic
04951                                                              counter SSO_WQ_INT_PC[PC]==0 and
04952                                                              SSO_WQ_INT_THRX[TC_EN]==1 and at least one of:
04953                                                                - SSO_WQ_INT_CNTX[IQ_CNT] > 0
04954                                                                - SSO_WQ_INT_CNTX[DS_CNT] > 0 */
04955 #else
04956     uint64_t wq_int                       : 64;
04957 #endif
04958     } s;
04959     struct cvmx_sso_wq_int_s              cn68xx;
04960     struct cvmx_sso_wq_int_s              cn68xxp1;
04961 };
04962 typedef union cvmx_sso_wq_int cvmx_sso_wq_int_t;
04963 
04964 /**
04965  * cvmx_sso_wq_int_cnt#
04966  *
04967  * CSR reserved addresses: (64): 0x7200..0x73f8
04968  * CSR align addresses: ===========================================================================================================
04969  * SSO_WQ_INT_CNTX = SSO Work Queue Interrupt Count Register
04970  *                   (one per group)
04971  *
04972  * Contains a read-only copy of the counts used to trigger work queue
04973  * interrupts.  For more information regarding this register, see the interrupt
04974  * section.
04975  */
04976 union cvmx_sso_wq_int_cntx {
04977     uint64_t u64;
04978     struct cvmx_sso_wq_int_cntx_s {
04979 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04980     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
04981     uint64_t tc_cnt                       : 4;  /**< Time counter current value for group X
04982                                                          HW sets TC_CNT to SSO_WQ_INT_THRX[TC_THR] whenever:
04983                                                            - corresponding SSO_WQ_INT_CNTX[IQ_CNT]==0 and
04984                                                              corresponding SSO_WQ_INT_CNTX[DS_CNT]==0
04985                                                            - corresponding SSO_WQ_INT[WQ_INT<X>] is written
04986                                                              with a 1 by SW
04987                                                            - corresponding SSO_WQ_IQ_DIS[IQ_DIS<X>] is written
04988                                                              with a 1 by SW
04989                                                            - corresponding SSO_WQ_INT_THRX is written by SW
04990                                                            - TC_CNT==1 and periodic counter
04991                                                              SSO_WQ_INT_PC[PC]==0
04992                                                          Otherwise, HW decrements TC_CNT whenever the
04993                                                          periodic counter SSO_WQ_INT_PC[PC]==0.
04994                                                          TC_CNT is 0 whenever SSO_WQ_INT_THRX[TC_THR]==0. */
04995     uint64_t reserved_26_27               : 2;
04996     uint64_t ds_cnt                       : 12; /**< De-schedule executable count for group X */
04997     uint64_t reserved_12_13               : 2;
04998     uint64_t iq_cnt                       : 12; /**< Input queue executable count for group X */
04999 #else
05000     uint64_t iq_cnt                       : 12;
05001     uint64_t reserved_12_13               : 2;
05002     uint64_t ds_cnt                       : 12;
05003     uint64_t reserved_26_27               : 2;
05004     uint64_t tc_cnt                       : 4;
05005     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
05006 #endif
05007     } s;
05008     struct cvmx_sso_wq_int_cntx_s         cn68xx;
05009     struct cvmx_sso_wq_int_cntx_s         cn68xxp1;

05047 /**
05048  * cvmx_sso_wq_int_thr#
05049  *
05050  * CSR reserved addresses: (96): 0x6100..0x63f8
05051  * CSR align addresses: ===========================================================================================================
05052  * SSO_WQ_INT_THR(0..63) = SSO Work Queue Interrupt Threshold Registers
05053  *                         (one per group)
05054  *
05055  * Contains the thresholds for enabling and setting work queue interrupts.  For
05056  * more information, see the interrupt section.
05057  *
05058  * Note: Up to 16 of the SSO's internal storage buffers can be allocated
05059  * for hardware use and are therefore not available for incoming work queue
05060  * entries.  Additionally, any WS that is not in the EMPTY state consumes a
05061  * buffer.  Thus in a 32 PP system, it is not advisable to set either IQ_THR or
05062  * DS_THR to greater than 2048 - 16 - 32*2 = 1968.  Doing so may prevent the
05063  * interrupt from ever triggering.
05064  *
05065  * Priorities for QOS levels 0..7
05066  */
05067 union cvmx_sso_wq_int_thrx {
05068     uint64_t u64;
05069     struct cvmx_sso_wq_int_thrx_s {
05070 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05071     uint64_t reserved_33_63               : 31;
05072     uint64_t tc_en                        : 1;  /**< Time counter interrupt enable for group X
05073                                                          TC_EN must be zero when TC_THR==0 */
05074     uint64_t tc_thr                       : 4;  /**< Time counter interrupt threshold for group X
05075                                                          When TC_THR==0, SSO_WQ_INT_CNTX[TC_CNT] is zero */
05076     uint64_t reserved_26_27               : 2;
05077     uint64_t ds_thr                       : 12; /**< De-schedule count threshold for group X
05078                                                          DS_THR==0 disables the threshold interrupt */
05079     uint64_t reserved_12_13               : 2;
05080     uint64_t iq_thr                       : 12; /**< Input queue count threshold for group X
05081                                                          IQ_THR==0 disables the threshold interrupt */
05082 #else
05083     uint64_t iq_thr                       : 12;
05084     uint64_t reserved_12_13               : 2;
05085     uint64_t ds_thr                       : 12;
05086     uint64_t reserved_26_27               : 2;
05087     uint64_t tc_thr                       : 4;
05088     uint64_t tc_en                        : 1;
05089     uint64_t reserved_33_63               : 31;
05090 #endif
05091     } s;
05092     struct cvmx_sso_wq_int_thrx_s         cn68xx;
05093     struct cvmx_sso_wq_int_thrx_s         cn68xxp1;
